The legislative intent behind the establishment of a Small Claims Division in the Local Courts was (and remains) to dispense with “the formality and procedural intricacies of the adversarial system where small claims are concerned and to provide litigants in such matters with a forum designed to achieve a fast, cheap, informal, but final resolution of their disputes” (Attorney-General’s Second Reading speech, Hansard, 22 November 1990, p 10,415). The overriding purpose of CPA is to facilitate the just, quick and cheap resolution of the real issues in the proceedings: (CPA 
s 56(1)
). See also Practice Note Civ 1 “Case Management of Civil Proceedings in the Local Court” at [LC Civ 1 of 2011], cl 3.3.

UCPR 
Pt 16
 (“Default judgment”) applies in the SCD, with the sole exception of 
r 16.4
, which deals with default judgment on a claim for possession of land. In other words, the procedure as regards default judgment on a claim for detention of goods (
r 16.5
), default judgment on a claim for a debt or liquidated demand (
r 16.6
), default judgment on a claim for unliquidated damages (
r 16.7
), default judgment on mixed claims (
r 16.8
), and judgment for costs alone after other claims have been satisfied (
r 16.9
) applies as well in the SCD as in the GD.

any application for the inspection of property (under UCPR 
r 23.8
), or

matters for which fixed costs are prescribed under Legal Profession Act 2004 
Pt 3.2
